As we start a new month, we invite you to join us to Go The Distance For Doug.

Westside Board of Education member Doug Krenzer is bravely battling cancer for the second time. A wonderful family friend and Westside grad Rebecca Hansen organized Team Distance For Doug to show Doug support and to raise money in his honor for the Leukemia and Lymphoma Society.

WE CHALLENGE YOU to commit to 50 miles in September - walking, biking, running - and share #DistanceForDoug .

Mr. Krenzer - you are our Warrior, and we've got your back!

***

If you'd like to join Doug's team or donate, you can also click here: https://fundraisers.hakuapp.com/teams/distance-for-doug?fbclid=IwAR1UnJBRe6TtIfs2JsiiX7bpgB-cc4_qflpI1-rtwPk0C2cuKBs7y2kB-ic

IMPORTANT: Westside plans to shift to 50% capacity at WHS & WMS beginning on Thursday, September 3rd, with hopes of returning to GREEN MODE/100% capacity September 17. Full details included in a message from Dr. Mike Lucas below.

A sincere THANK YOU to our entire community for working with us during this pandemic. To our teachers and staff - you are simply incredible, and we cannot say enough about your determination, dedication to our students, and support of each other. To our parents, you have made this possible! Thank you for your ongoing engagement and support at home, and your positive messages of encouragement to our staff and administration. And to our students - WE ARE SO HAPPY to see you again. Everything we do, we do for you!

Questions? Please email feedback@westside66.net

#WeAreWestside

post_text:
To all parents, sending your children to school next week... DON'T BLINK.

Turning the clock back to August of 2007, when Hannah-Kate and Jack Kinney started Kindergarten at Loveland Elementary! These Warriors just graduated from Westside High School, and will leave home this week to begin their next chapter. From Mom, Jane Hanigan-Kinney: "Total denial that our kids' years as Westside Warriors is a chapter now closed.
It was a ride better than any of us could ever possibly imagined (thank you, Westside!) -- and one that we, as their parents, are sad to see them leave behind. But, we couldn't be more excited to see what they each accomplish in the next chapter!"

#WeAreWestside

District leaders from Westside Community Schools will share updates about plans for school in Fall of 2020. Westside will start in YELLOW status on August 18, and continue through Sept. 4 before reevaluating recommendations for public health experts.

We will not be responding to questions directly on this thread. PLEASE EMAIL FEEDBACK@WESTSIDE66.NET. We will respond to every email we receive. Thank you!

RULES FOR THIS FORUM:
1) Please be respectful. Any derogatory comments will be deleted.
2) Please understand that any decisions made in the coming weeks will not be met with 100% approval, but made with the best intent for all Westside students, families and staff.
3) Due to high volume and to ensure we respond to all questions accurately and quickly, please email your questions/comments to feedback@westside66.net.

We have three other sites that will be open and distributing free meals for children ages 1-18. All sites will be open through 12:30pm today.

- Westgate Elementary, 7802 Hascall
- Prairie Lane Elementary/Swing School, 3534 S. 108th St.
- Westbrook Elementary, 1312 Robertson Drive

This means there will NOT be a late afternoon pickup available today. If your family needs assistance for this week and cannot make it to the other sites by 12:30, please reach out to Director of Student Services Robert Aranda at aranda.robert@westside66.net.

As we draw one week closer to our August 18 start of the 2020-2021 school year, we invite you to review our updated Pandemic Plan for Westside Community Schools, as of July 14. This document is attached to this email. Please note: this plan will continue to change and evolve. District leaders are meeting with a panel of medical experts next week who will provide us with updated recommendations and changes. Our hope in sharing this plan with you is to keep you updated with what we know now as you plan for fall. Items listed in RED on this rough draft are new/updated since our last rough draft version.

THANK YOU, Westside students, families and staff members, for your ongoing patience, support and engagement as we navigate these challenges. And please join us THURSDAY NIGHT AT 6PM for our next Community Forum to hear more about our Pandemic Plan directly from Dr. Lucas and district leaders.

post_text:
Westside Community Schools will launch the WE-SIDE Community Council later this summer. This stands for Welcoming Equity Support Inclusion Dignity Everyone. In light of recent events, we have been talking to employees throughout our district to discuss race relations and what Westside can do to better support our black students and staff during this difficult and divisive time. We want to make our black students and staff, and all students and staff, feel welcomed and valued throughout our district. We want to focus on things that bring us TOGETHER and not force us apart with labels and unknowns.

We hope you will consider joining us on June 24th at 6pm ONLINE (here on Facebook) or at Westside High School (Little Theater) in a social-distancing manner, to discuss what we‚Äôve done, what we will be doing, and how we want to move forward from here. Please click below for additional details.

WE are Westside.

https://westside66.org/news/district-to-host-we-side-forum/

We are excited to share that work at Prairie Lane continues to move along well! Exterior wall framing is nearly complete for the new portion of the building. Wall insulation, interior wall framing and rough-in will start in the next few weeks. The interior concrete slab on grade for the classroom portion of the building is complete.

Next: brick and roofing for the new addition will begin this month and continue throughout the summer. The gym concrete block exterior walls will be complete this week with interior concrete slab on grade and roof steel being installed in mid-June.

Thank you as always for your continued engagement and support!

Westside Community Schools

Dear Families of Students Entering 6th and 7th Grade,

We wanted to make you aware of a fun summer opportunity occurring this summer in a different way. Due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, Westside Middle School's annual summer show choir camp has moved to a digital platform. Camp is open to any student entering 6th, 7th and 8th grade in the fall of 2020. We wanted to make you aware of a fun summer opportunity occurring this summer in a different way. Due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, Westside Middle School's annual summer show choir camp has moved to a digital platform. Camp is open to any student entering 6th, 7th and 8th grade in the fall of 2020. Many a proud Bulldog has gone on to perform as part of the Westside Middle School and later Westside High School Show Choirs. For more information, check out the following website. Thank you!

post_text:
We have great news to report from the home of the future Prairie Lane Elementary! Crews have been hard at work without disruption, as it is easier to maintain social distancing guidelines on most job sites.

The steel frame for most of the building is nearly complete, and the last portion of the building frame to be constructed is the new gym on the northeast side of the site. The masonry walls and steel roof should be completed in early June. Exterior wall framing and roofing work will begin in the coming weeks. Plumbing, HVAC and electrical rough-in work, along with concrete slab on grade, are the next activities inside the building footprint. Work to construct the area at Hascall St. will begin in late May and run through June.

Thank you all for your engagement and support as we continue our work on this exciting project!

The 2019 Westside Foundation Annual Report is now available to view online! Learn more about how $2.7 million was invested to support students, teachers and facilities. The annual report features new grants, interesting stories and exciting updates to the district.

We invite you to check out all the impressive work that‚Äôs being done for Westside Community Schools, including the new state-of-the-art welding, fabrication and manufacturing lab, STEAM programs and innovative technology for the theater program.

Superintendent Mike Lucas (hired in 2019), Westside Foundation President Laura Illiff and Development Director Terry Hanna pay tribute to the Westside Foundation and its tremendous support in ensuring a bright future for students, staff and the community.

Click below to read the full 2019 Annual Report!

shared_text:
Mike Lucas
May 7 at 11:51 AM ¬∑

We have now been forced to hire a uniformed security guard to help monitor activity at our WHS athletic facilities.

Again, we want people to be able to come up and walk and exercise in a safe, social distancing manner. We appreciate the way our students and patrons are using the facilities. We need visitors to do the right thing as well.

The uniformed security guard is prepared to issue citations to those that want to play 7 on 7 football games, soccer matches, etc. that are NOT safe during current social distancing guidelines.

Acceptable - small groups of folks working on drills, jogging/walking, playing frisbee, etc. in a spaced out manner.

UNacceptable - touch football games, soccer matches, and large group gatherings of any sort.

May 5 at 3:26 PM ¬∑

Westside‚Äôs annual Battle of the Books competition, sponsored by the Westside Community Council, was scheduled to take place on Saturday, March 21. We were expecting 58 teams and almost 250 kids to participate this year!

Although we were disappointed to have to cancel the event, we were able to use the competition questions that were already created to set up 8 rounds of Battle of the Books from home! The teams have been meeting virtually to answer battle questions in Kahoot! quizzes. Kahoot! is a game-based learning app. So far, approximately 40 teams have competed in each of three rounds, and we have five more rounds scheduled through the end of the month.

Congratulations to all the teams on their hard work this year preparing for the Battle. And THANK YOU to the hardworking volunteers who made this possible: Jackie Anderson, Mary Schafer, and Ashley Wegner

Angela Li, flute - FINALIST
Ashleigh Madsen, trumpet - FINALIST
